What is APR?APR stands for Annual Percentage Rate. It's a measure used to compare the yearly cost of borrowing money or earning it on savings across different products or institutions. The APR includes not only the interest rate but also any additional fees or costs associated with the transaction, providing a more comprehensive view of the total cost.

For example, if you're taking out a loan, the APR will give you an idea of what the yearly cost is going to be, including both the interest and any other charges. The same applies when saving money; it shows you how much your savings are growing each year after accounting for all fees and costs.

It's important to note that different lenders may calculate APR differently, so always make sure to compare apples with apples when looking at financial products.yes
